======================================================================
Q2: AMONG ERRORS ONLY — Does the ratio shift over time?
======================================================================

Total errors: 206
  Perceptual: 161
  Semantic:   45

--- Error composition by test ---
Test  N err    Perceptual      Semantic
---------------------------------------------
  T1     38    37 ( 97.4%)     1 (  2.6%)
  T2     30    23 ( 76.7%)     7 ( 23.3%)
  T3     58    43 ( 74.1%)    15 ( 25.9%)
  T4     80    58 ( 72.5%)    22 ( 27.5%)

Participants with >=1 error: 80 / 100
Participants with >=2 errors: 49
Errors per participant: mean=2.6, median=2, max=10

--- GEE: P(perceptual | error) ~ log(Days) ---
  Independence correlation (many singletons)
  Intercept: b=1.6635, SE=0.2284, OR=5.278 [3.373, 8.258], p=0.0000
  log_Days: b=-0.4492, SE=0.1298, OR=0.638 [0.495, 0.823], p=0.0005

--- GEE: P(perceptual | error) ~ Days ---
  Intercept: b=2.0304, SE=0.3026, OR=7.617 [4.209, 13.783], p=0.0000
  Days: b=-0.1944, SE=0.0630, OR=0.823 [0.728, 0.931], p=0.0020

--- Simple logistic (no clustering) as robustness check ---
  Days: b=-0.1944, OR=0.823, p=0.0068

--- Q2 Summary ---
The proportion of errors that are perceptual DECREASES over time:
  T1: 97.4% perceptual → T4: 72.5% perceptual
This means semantic errors are growing as a share of total errors,
even though both types increase in absolute terms.

