--- KEY ITEM FINDINGS ---

Items with highest PERCEPTUAL error rates:
          Toaster: 29.0% perceptual errors
           Hammer: 26.0% perceptual errors
          Cutlery: 19.0% perceptual errors
             Duck: 19.0% perceptual errors
       Frying Pan: 9.0% perceptual errors

Items with highest SEMANTIC error rates:
          Glasses: 17.0% semantic errors
           Laptop: 8.0% semantic errors
        Newspaper: 3.0% semantic errors
          Toaster: 2.0% semantic errors
             Lamp: 2.0% semantic errors

--- Item design implications ---
Toaster (29%), Hammer (26%), Cutlery (19%), Duck (19%):
  These items may have visually similar foils (hard perceptual discrimination).
  This is an item DESIGN property, not a memory process per se.

Glasses (17% semantic, only 1% perceptual):
  This item is anomalous — participants lose category knowledge.
  Possibly confused with a different object category entirely.

Laptop (8% semantic, 4% perceptual):
  Second-highest semantic error rate — similar pattern to Glasses.

Concentration: Top 4 items account for 93/161 (58%) of all perceptual errors
  (Toaster + Hammer + Cutlery + Duck)
Glasses alone accounts for 17/45 (38%) of all semantic errors

